.SS "Special Start-of-Pattern Items"

.PP
A number of options that can be passed to \fIcompile/2\fR can also be set by special items at the start of a pattern. These are not Perl-compatible, but are provided to make these options accessible to pattern writers who are not able to change the program that processes the pattern. Any number of these items may appear, but they must all be together right at the start of the pattern string, and the letters must be in upper case.

.PP
\fIUTF support\fR

.PP
Unicode support is basically UTF-8 based. To use Unicode characters, you either call \fIcompile/2\fR or \fIrun/3\fR with option \fIunicode\fR, or the pattern must start with one of these special sequences: \fI(*UTF)\fR, which is equivalent to setting \fIunicode\fR. Note that with these instructions, the automatic conversion of lists to UTF-8 is not performed by the \fIre\fR functions. Therefore, using these sequences is not recommended. Add option \fIunicode\fR when running \fIcompile/2\fR instead.

.PP
Some applications that allow their users to supply patterns may wish to restrict them to non-UTF data for security reasons. If the \fInever_utf\fR option is passed to \fIcompile/2\fR, \fI(*UTF)\fR is not allowed, and its appearance in a pattern causes an error.

.PP
\fIUnicode Property Support\fR

.PP
Another special sequence that may appear at the start of a pattern is \fI(*UCP)\fR. This has the same effect as setting the \fIucp\fR option: it causes sequences such as \fI\\d\fR and \fI\\w\fR to use Unicode properties to determine character types, instead of recognizing only characters with codes less than 256 via a lookup table. It also causes upper/lower casing operations to use Unicode properties for characters with code points greater than 127, even when UTF is not set. These behaviours can be changed within the pattern; see Internal Option Setting.

.PP
Some applications that allow their users to supply patterns may wish to restrict them for security reasons. If the \fInever_ucp\fR option is passed to \fIcompile/2\fR, \fI(*UCP)\fR is not allowed, and its appearance in a pattern causes an error.

.PP
\fILocking Out Empty String Matching\fR

.PP
Starting a pattern with \fI(*NOTEMPTY)\fR or \fI(*NOTEMPTY_ATSTART)\fR has the same effect as passing the \fInotempty\fR or \fInotempty_atstart\fR option to whichever matching function is subsequently called to match the pattern. These options lock out the matching of empty strings, either entirely, or only at the start of the subject.

.PP
\fIDisabling Start-Up Optimizations\fR

.PP
If a pattern starts with \fI(*NO_START_OPT)\fR, it has the same effect as setting the \fIno_start_optimize\fR option. This disables several optimizations for quickly reaching "no match" results.

.PP
\fIDisabling Automatic Anchoring\fR

.PP
If a pattern starts with \fI(*NO_DOTSTAR_ANCHOR)\fR. This disables optimizations that apply to patterns whose top-level branches all start with .* (match any number of arbitrary characters).

.PP
\fISetting Match Resource Limits\fR

.PP
The caller of \fIrun/3\fR can set a limit on this counter, which therefore limits the amount of computing resource used for a match. The maximum depth of nested backtracking can also be limited; this indirectly restricts the amount of heap memory that is used, but there is also an explicit memory limit that can be set.

.PP
These facilities are provided to catch runaway matches that are provoked by patterns with huge matching trees. A common example is a pattern with nested unlimited repeats applied to a long string that does not match. When one of these limits is reached, \fIrun/3\fR gives an error return. The limits can also be set by items at the start of the pattern of the form

.IP
.nf
(*LIMIT_HEAP=d)
(*LIMIT_MATCH=d)
(*LIMIT_DEPTH=d)

.fi

.PP
where d is any number of decimal digits. However, the value of the setting must be less than the value set as default for it to have any effect. In other words, the pattern writer can lower the limits set by the programmer, but not raise them. If there is more than one setting of one of these limits, the lower value is used. The heap limit is specified in kibibytes (units of 1024 bytes).

.PP
The default value for \fILIMIT_MATCH\fR and \fILIMIT_DEPTH\fR is 10,000,000 in the Erlang VM. Notice that the recursion limit does not affect the stack depth of the VM, as PCRE for Erlang is compiled in such a way that the match function never does recursion on the C stack.

.PP
Prior to release 10.30, LIMIT_DEPTH was called LIMIT_RECURSION. This name is still recognized for backwards compatibility.

.PP
\fINewline Conventions\fR

.PP
PCRE2 supports six different conventions for indicating line breaks in strings: a single CR (carriage return) character, a single LF (linefeed) character, the two-character sequence CRLF, any of the three preceding, any Unicode newline sequence, or the NUL character (binary zero).

.PP
It is also possible to specify a newline convention by starting a pattern string with one of the following sequences:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fICR)\fR* -  carriage return

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fILF)\fR* -  linefeed

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fICRLF)\fR* -  carriage return, followed by linefeed

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fIANYCRLF)\fR* -  any of the three above

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fIANY)\fR* -  all Unicode newline sequences

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fINUL)\fR* -  the NUL character (binary zero)

.RE

.PP
These override the default and the options given to the compiling function. For example, on a Unix system where LF is the default newline sequence, the pattern

.IP
.nf
(*CR)a.b

.fi

.PP
changes the convention to CR. That pattern matches "a\\nb" because LF is no longer a newline. If more than one of these settings is present, the last one is used.

.PP
The newline convention affects where the circumflex and dollar assertions are true. It also affects the interpretation of the dot metacharacter when \fIdotall\fR is not set, and the behaviour of \fI\\N\fR when not followed by an opening brace. However, it does not affect what the \fI\\R\fR escape sequence matches. By default, this is any Unicode newline sequence, for Perl compatibility. However, this can be changed; see the next section and the description of \fI\\R\fR in Newline Sequences. A change of \fI\\R\fR setting can be combined with a change of newline convention.

.PP
\fISpecifying What \fI\\R\fR Matches\fR

.PP
It is possible to restrict \fI\\R\fR to match only CR, LF, or CRLF (instead of the complete set of Unicode line endings) by setting the option \fIbsr_anycrlf\fR at compile time. This effect can also be achieved by starting a pattern with \fI(*BSR_ANYCRLF)\fR. For completeness, \fI(*BSR_UNICODE)\fR is also recognized, corresponding to \fIbsr_anycrlf\fR.

.SS "Characters and Metacharacters"

.PP
A regular expression is a pattern that is matched against a subject string from left to right. Most characters stand for themselves in a pattern, and match the corresponding characters in the subject. As a trivial example, the pattern

.IP
.nf
The quick brown fox

.fi

.PP
matches a portion of a subject string that is identical to itself. When caseless matching is specified (the \fIcaseless\fR option or (?i) within the pattern), letters are matched independently of case. Note that there are two ASCII characters, K and S, that, in addition to their lower case ASCII equivalents, are case-equivalent with Unicode U+212A (Kelvin sign) and U+017F (long S) respectively when either \fIunicode\fR or \fIucp\fR is set.

.PP
The power of regular expressions comes from the ability to include wild cards, character classes, alternatives, and repetitions in the pattern. These are encoded in the pattern by the use of \fImetacharacters\fR, which do not stand for themselves but instead are interpreted in some special way.

.PP
There are two different sets of metacharacters: those that are recognized anywhere in the pattern except within square brackets, and those that are recognized within square brackets. Outside square brackets, the metacharacters are as follows:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**`** -  general escape character with several uses

.RE
^
.RS 2
assert start of string (or line, in multiline mode)


.RE
$
.RS 2
assert end of string (or line, in multiline mode)


.RE
\&.
.RS 2
match any character except newline (by default)


.RE
[
.RS 2
start character class definition


.RE
|
.RS 2
start of alternative branch


.RE
(
.RS 2
start group or control verb


.RE
)
.RS 2
end group or control verb


.RE
*
.RS 2
0 or more quantifier


.RE
+
.RS 2
1 or more quantifier; also "possessive quantifier"


.RE
?
.RS 2
0 or 1 quantifier; also quantifier minimizer


.RE
{
.RS 2
potential start of min/max quantifier


.RE

.PP
Brace characters \fI{\fR and \fI}\fR are also used to enclose data for constructions such as \fI\\g{2}\fR or \fI\\k{name}\fR. In almost all uses of braces, space and/or horizontal tab characters that follow \fI{\fR or precede \fI}\fR are allowed and are ignored. In the case of quantifiers, they may also appear before or after the comma. 

.PP
Part of a pattern that is in square brackets is called a "character class". In a character class the only metacharacters are:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**`** -  general escape character

.RE
^
.RS 2
negate the class, but only if the first character


.RE
-
.RS 2
indicates character range


.RE
[
.RS 2
POSIX character class (if followed by POSIX syntax)


.RE
]
.RS 2
terminates the character class


.RE

.PP
If a pattern is compiled with the \fIextended\fR option, most white space in the pattern, other than in a character class, within a \fI\\Q...\\E\fR sequence, or between a \fI#\fR  outside a character class and the next newline, inclusive, is ignored. An escaping backslash can be used to include a white space or a # character as part of the pattern.

.PP
\fBNOTE: \fROnly these two characters are ignored, not the full set of pattern white space characters that are ignored outside a character class. Option settings can be changed within a pattern; see Internal Option Setting.


.PP
The following sections describe the use of each of the metacharacters.

.SS "Backslash"

.PP
The backslash character has several uses. Firstly, if it is followed by a character that is not a digit or a letter, it takes away any special meaning that character may have. This use of backslash as an escape character applies both inside and outside character classes.

.PP
For example, if you want to match a \fI*\fR  character, you must write \fI\\*\fR in the pattern. This escaping action applies whether or not the following character would otherwise be interpreted as a metacharacter, so it is always safe to precede a non-alphanumeric with backslash to specify that it stands for itself. In particular, if you want to match a backslash, you write \\`.

.PP
Only ASCII digits and letters have any special meaning after a backslash. All other characters (in particular, those whose code points are greater than 127) are treated as literals.

.PP
If you want to treat all characters in a sequence as literals, you can do so by putting them between \fI\\Q\fR and \fI\\E\fR. Note that this includes white space even when the \fIextended\fR option is set so that most other white space is ignored. The behaviour is different from Perl in that \fI$\fR and \fI@\fR are handled as literals in \fI\\Q...\\E\fR sequences in PCRE2, whereas in Perl, \fI$\fR and \fI@\fR cause variable interpolation. Also, Perl does "double-quotish backslash interpolation" on any backslashes between \fI\\Q\fR and \fI\\E\fR which, its documentation says, "may lead to confusing results". PCRE2 treats a backslash between \fI\\Q\fR and \fI\\E\fR just like any other character. Note the following examples:

Pattern
.RS 2
PCRE2 matches   Perl matches


.RE
\Qabc$xyz\E
.RS 2
abc$xyz        abc followed by the contents of $xyz


.RE
\Qabc$xyz\E
.RS 2
abc$xyz       abc$xyz


.RE
\Qabc\E$\Qxyz\E
.RS 2
abc$xyz        abc$xyz


.RE
\QA\B\E
.RS 2
A\B            A\B


.RE
\Q\E
.RS 2
\              \E


.RE

.PP
The \fI\\Q...\\E\fR sequence is recognized both inside and outside character classes. An isolated \fI\\E\fR that is not preceded by \fI\\Q\fR is ignored. If \fI\\Q\fR is not followed by \fI\\E\fR later in the pattern, the literal interpretation continues to the end of the pattern (that is, \fI\\E\fR is assumed at the end). If the isolated \fI\\Q\fR is inside a character class, this causes an error, because the character class is then not terminated by a closing square bracket.

.PP
Another difference from Perl is that any appearance of \fI\\Q\fR or \fI\\E\fR inside what might otherwise be a quantifier causes PCRE2 not to recognize the sequence as a quantifier. Perl recognizes a quantifier if (redundantly) either of the numbers is inside \fI\\Q...\\E\fR, but not if the separating comma is. When not recognized as a quantifier a sequence such as \fI{\\Q1\\E,2}\fR is treated as the literal string "{1,2}".

.PP
\fINon-Printing Characters\fR

.PP
A second use of backslash provides a way of encoding non-printing characters in patterns in a visible manner. There is no restriction on the appearance of non-printing characters in a pattern, but when a pattern is being prepared by text editing, it is often easier to use one of the following escape sequences instead of the binary character it represents. In an ASCII or Unicode environment, these escapes are as follows:

\a
.RS 2
alarm, that is, the BEL character (hex 07)


.RE
\cx
.RS 2
"control-x", where x is a non-control ASCII character


.RE
\e
.RS 2
escape (hex 1B)


.RE
\f
.RS 2
form feed (hex 0C)


.RE
\n
.RS 2
linefeed (hex 0A)


.RE
\r
.RS 2
carriage return (hex 0D) (but see below)


.RE
\t
.RS 2
tab (hex 09)


.RE
\0dd
.RS 2
character with octal code 0dd


.RE
\ddd
.RS 2
character with octal code ddd, or back reference


.RE
\o{ddd..}
.RS 2
character with octal code ddd..


.RE
\xhh
.RS 2
character with hex code hh


.RE
\x{hhh..}
.RS 2
character with hex code hhh..


.RE
\N{U+hhh..}
.RS 2
character with Unicode hex code point hhh..


.RE

.PP
A description of how back references work is given later, following the discussion of parenthesized groups.

.PP
By default, after \fI\\x\fR that is not followed by \fI{\fR, one or two hexadecimal digits are read (letters can be in upper or lower case). If the character that follows \fI\\x\fR is neither \fI{\fR nor a hexadecimal digit, an error occurs. This is different from Perl's default behaviour, which generates a NUL character, but is in line with the behaviour of Perl's 'strict' mode in re.

.PP
Any number of hexadecimal digits may appear between \fI\\x{\fR and \fI}\fR. If a character other than a hexadecimal digit appears between \fI\\x{\fR and \fI}\fR, or if there is no terminating \fI}\fR, an error occurs.

.PP
Characters whose code points are less than 256 can be defined by either of the two syntaxes for \fI\\x\fR or by an octal sequence. There is no difference in the way they are handled. For example, \fI\\xdc\fR is exactly the same as \fI\\x{dc}\fR or \fI\\334\fR. However, using the braced versions does make such sequences easier to read.

.PP
The \fI\\N{U+hhh..}\fR escape sequence is recognized only when PCRE2 is operating in UTF mode. Perl also uses \fI\\N{name}\fR to specify characters by Unicode name; PCRE2 does not support this. Note that when \fI\\N\fR is not followed by an opening brace (curly bracket) it has an entirely different meaning, matching any character that is not a newline.

.PP
There are some legacy applications where the escape sequence \fI\\r\fR is expected to match a newline.

.PP
An error occurs if \fI\\c\fR is not followed by a character whose ASCII code point is in the range 32 to 126. The precise effect of \fI\\cx\fR is as follows: if x is a lower case letter, it is converted to upper case. Then bit 6 of the character (hex 40) is inverted. Thus \fI\\cA\fR to \fI\\cZ\fR become hex 01 to hex 1A (A is 41, Z is 5A), but \fI\\c{\fR becomes hex 3B ({ is 7B), and \fI\\c\fR; becomes hex 7B (; is 3B). If the code unit following \fI\\c\fR has a code point less than 32 or greater than 126, a compile-time error occurs.

.PP
\fIOctal Escapes and Back References\fR

.PP
The escape \fI\\o\fR must be followed by a sequence of octal digits, enclosed in braces. An error occurs if this is not the case. This escape provides a way of specifying character code points as octal numbers greater than 0777, and it also allows octal numbers and backreferences to be unambiguously distinguished.

.PP
If braces are not used, after \fI\\0\fR up to two further octal digits are read.

.PP
Inside a character class, when a backslash is followed by any octal digit, up to three octal digits are read to generate a code point. Any subsequent digits stand for themselves. The sequences \fI\\8\fR and \fI\\9\fR are treated as the literal characters "8" and "9".

.PP
Outside a character class, Perl's handling of a backslash followed by a digit other than 0 is complicated by ambiguity, and Perl has changed over time, causing PCRE2 also to change.

.PP
For greater clarity and unambiguity, it is best to avoid following \\e by a digit greater than zero. Instead, use \fI\\o{...}\fR or \fI\\x{...}\fR to specify numerical character code points, and \fI\\g{...}\fR to specify backreferences.

.PP
\fIPerl Rules for Non-Class Backslash 1-9\fR

.PP
All the digits that follow the backslash are read as a decimal number. If the number is less than 10, begins with the digit 8 or 9, or if there are at least that many previous capture groups in the expression, the entire sequence is taken as a back reference. Otherwise, up to three octal digits are read to form a character code. For example:

\040
.RS 2
is another way of writing an ASCII space


.RE
\40
.RS 2
is the same, provided there are fewer than 40 previous capture groups


.RE
\7
.RS 2
is always a backreference


.RE
\11
.RS 2
might be a backreference, or another way of writing a tab


.RE
\011
.RS 2
is always a tab


.RE
\0113
.RS 2
is a tab followed by the character "3"


.RE
\113
.RS 2
might be a backreference, otherwise the character with octal code 113


.RE
\377
.RS 2
might be a backreference, otherwise the value 255 (decimal)


.RE
\81
.RS 2
is always a backreference


.RE

.PP
Note that octal values of 100 or greater that are specified using this syntax must not be introduced by a leading zero, because no more than three octal digits are ever read.

.PP
\fIPython Rules for Non-Class Backslash 1-9\fR

.PP
If there are at least three octal digits after the backslash, exactly three are read as an octal code point number, but the value must be no greater than \fI\\377\fR, even in modes where higher code point values are supported. Any subsequent digits stand for themselves. If there are fewer than three octal digits, the sequence is taken as a decimal back reference. Thus, for example, \fI\\12\fR is always a back reference, independent of how many captures there are in the pattern. An error is generated for a reference to a non-existent capturing group.

.PP
\fIConstraints on Character Values\fR

.PP
Characters that are specified using octal or hexadecimal numbers are limited to certain values, as follows:

8-bit non-UTF mode
.RS 2
no greater than 0xff


.RE
8-bit UTF-8 mode
.RS 2
no greater than 0x10ffff and a valid code point


.RE

.PP
Invalid Unicode code points are all those in the range 0xd800 to 0xdfff (the so-called "surrogate" code points).

.PP
\fIEscape Sequences in Character Classes\fR

.PP
All the sequences that define a single character value can be used both inside and outside character classes. In addition, inside a character class, \fI\\b\fR is interpreted as the backspace character (hex 08).

.PP
When not followed by an opening brace, \fI\\N\fR is not allowed in a character class. \fI\\B\fR, \fI\\R\fR, and \fI\\X\fR are not special inside a character class. Like other unrecognized alphabetic escape sequences, they cause an error. Outside a character class, these sequences have different meanings.

.PP
\fIUnsupported Escape Sequences\fR

.PP
In Perl, the sequences \fI\\F\fR, \fI\\l\fR, \fI\\L\fR, \fI\\u\fR, and \fI\\U\fR are recognized by its string handler and used to modify the case of following characters. By default, PCRE2 does not support these escape sequences in patterns.

.PP
\fIAbsolute and Relative Backreferences\fR

.PP
The sequence \fI\\g\fR followed by a signed or unsigned number, optionally enclosed in braces, is an absolute or relative backreference. A named backreference can be coded as \fI\\g{name}\fR. Backreferences are discussed later, following the discussion of parenthesized groups.

.PP
\fIAbsolute and Relative Subroutine Calls\fR

.PP
For compatibility with Oniguruma, the non-Perl syntax \fI\\g\fR followed by a name or a number enclosed either in angle brackets or single quotes, is an alternative syntax for referencing a capture group as a subroutine. Details are discussed later. Note that \fI\\g{...}\fR (Perl syntax) and \fI\\g<...>\fR (Oniguruma syntax) are \fInot\fR synonymous. The former is a backreference; the latter is a subroutine call.

.PP
\fIGeneric Character Types\fR

.PP
Another use of backslash is for specifying generic character types:

\d
.RS 2
any decimal digit


.RE
\D
.RS 2
any character that is not a decimal digit


.RE
\h
.RS 2
any horizontal white space character


.RE
\H
.RS 2
any character that is not a horizontal white space character


.RE
\N
.RS 2
any character that is not a newline


.RE
\s
.RS 2
any white space character


.RE
\S
.RS 2
any character that is not a white space character


.RE
\v
.RS 2
any vertical white space character


.RE
\V
.RS 2
any character that is not a vertical white space character


.RE
\w
.RS 2
any "word" character


.RE
\W
.RS 2
any "non-word" character


.RE

.PP
The \fI\\N\fR escape sequence has the same meaning as the "." metacharacter when \fIdotall\fR is not set, but setting \fIdotall\fR does not change the meaning of \fI\\N\fR. Note that when \fI\\N\fR is followed by an opening brace it has a different meaning. See Non-Printing Characters. Perl also uses \fI\\N{name}\fR to specify characters by Unicode name; PCRE2 does not support this.

.PP
Each pair of lower and upper case escape sequences partitions the complete set of characters into two disjoint sets. Any given character matches one, and only one, of each pair. The sequences can appear both inside and outside character classes. They each match one character of the appropriate type. If the current matching point is at the end of the subject string, all of them fail, because there is no character to match.

.PP
The default \fI\\s\fR characters are HT (9), LF (10), VT (11), FF (12), CR (13), and space (32), which are defined as white space in the "C" locale. This list may vary if locale-specific matching is taking place. For example, in some locales the "non-breaking space" character (\fI\\xA0\fR) is recognized as white space, and in others the VT character is not.

.PP
A "word" character is an underscore or any character that is a letter or digit. By default, the definition of letters and digits is controlled by PCRE2's low-valued character tables, and may vary if locale-specific matching is taking place. For example, in a French locale such as "fr_FR" in Unix-like systems, or "french" in Windows, some character codes greater than 127 are used for accented letters, and these are then matched by \fI\\w\fR. The use of locales with Unicode is discouraged.

.PP
By default, characters whose code points are greater than 127 never match \fI\\d\fR, \fI\\s\fR, or \fI\\w\fR, and always match \fI\\D\fR, \fI\\S\fR, and \fI\\W\fR, although this may be different for characters in the range 128-255 when locale-specific matching is happening. These escape sequences retain their original meanings from before Unicode support was available, mainly for efficiency reasons. If the \fIucp\fR option is set, the behaviour is changed so that Unicode properties are used to determine character types, as follows:

\d
.RS 2
Any character that matches 
\fI\\p{Nd}\fR (decimal digit)

.RE

\s
.RS 2
Any character that matches 
\fI\\p{Z}\fR or \fI\\h\fR or \fI\\v\fR

.RE

\w
.RS 2
Any character that matches 
\fI\\p{L}\fR, \fI\\p{N}\fR, \fI\\p{Mn}\fR, or \fI\\p{Pc}\fR

.RE

.PP
The addition of \fI\\p{Mn}\fR (non-spacing mark) and the replacement of an explicit test for underscore with a test for \fI\\p{Pc}\fR (connector punctuation) happened in PCRE2 release 10.43. This brings PCRE2 into line with Perl.

.PP
The upper case escapes match the inverse sets of characters. Note that \fI\\d\fR matches only decimal digits, whereas \fI\\w\fR matches any Unicode digit, as well as other character categories. Note also that \fIucp\fR affects \fI\\b\fR, and \fI\\B\fR because they are defined in terms of \fI\\w\fR and \fI\\W\fR. Matching these sequences is noticeably slower when \fIucp\fR is set.

.PP
The effect of \fIucp\fR on any one of these escape sequences can be negated by the options within a pattern by means of an Internal Option Setting.

.PP
The sequences \fI\\h\fR, \fI\\H\fR, \fI\\v\fR, and \fI\\V\fR, in contrast to the other sequences, which match only ASCII characters by default, always match a specific list of code points, whether or not \fIucp\fR is set. The horizontal space characters are:

U+0009
.RS 2
