.RE

U+180E
.RS 2
Mongolian vowel separator


.RE

U+2000
.RS 2
En quad


.RE

U+2001
.RS 2
Em quad


.RE

U+2002
.RS 2
En space


.RE

U+2003
.RS 2
Em space


.RE

U+2004
.RS 2
Three-per-em space


.RE

U+2005
.RS 2
Four-per-em space


.RE

U+2006
.RS 2
Six-per-em space


.RE

U+2007
.RS 2
Figure space


.RE

U+2008
.RS 2
Punctuation space


.RE

U+2009
.RS 2
Thin space


.RE

U+200A
.RS 2
Hair space


.RE

U+202F
.RS 2
Narrow no-break space


.RE

U+205F
.RS 2
Medium mathematical space


.RE

U+3000
.RS 2
Ideographic space


.RE

.PP
The vertical space characters are:

U+000A
.RS 2
Linefeed (LF)


.RE

U+000B
.RS 2
Vertical tab (VT)


.RE

U+000C
.RS 2
Form feed (FF)


.RE

U+000D
.RS 2
Carriage return (CR)


.RE

U+0085
.RS 2
Next line (NEL)


.RE

U+2028
.RS 2
Line separator


.RE

U+2029
.RS 2
Paragraph separator


.RE

.PP
In 8-bit, non-UTF-8 mode, only the characters with code points less than 256 are relevant.

.PP
\fINewline Sequences\fR

.PP
Outside a character class, by default, the escape sequence \fI\\R\fR matches any Unicode newline sequence. In 8-bit non-UTF-8 mode \fI\\R\fR is equivalent to the following:

.IP
.nf
(?>\\r\\n|\\n|\\x0b|\\f|\\r|\\x85)

.fi

.PP
This is an example of an "atomic group", details of which are given below. This particular group matches either the two-character sequence CR followed by LF, or one of the single characters LF (linefeed, U+000A), VT (vertical tab, U+000B), FF (form feed, U+000C), CR (carriage return, U+000D), or NEL (next line, U+0085). Because this is an atomic group, the two-character sequence is treated as a single unit that cannot be split.

.PP
In other modes, two additional characters whose code points are greater than 255 are added: LS (line separator, U+2028) and PS (paragraph separator, U+2029). Unicode support is not needed for these characters to be recognized.

.PP
It is possible to restrict \fI\\R\fR to match only CR, LF, or CRLF (instead of the complete set of Unicode line endings) by setting the option \fIbsr_anycrlf\fR at compile time. (BSR is an abbreviation for "backslash R".) This can be made the default when PCRE2 is built; if this is the case, the other behaviour can be requested via the \fIbsr_anycrlf\fR option. It is also possible to specify these settings by starting a pattern string with one of the following sequences:


.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fIBSR_ANYCRLF)\fR* -  CR, LF, or CRLF only

.RE

.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}.PP
**(\fIBSR_UNICODE)\fR* -  any Unicode newline sequence

.RE

.PP
These override the default and the options given to the compiling function. Note that these special settings, which are not Perl-compatible, are recognized only at the very start of a pattern, and that they must be in upper case. If more than one of them is present, the last one is used. They can be combined with a change of newline convention; for example, a pattern can start with:

.IP
.nf
(*ANY)(*BSR_ANYCRLF)

.fi

.PP
They can also be combined with the \fI(*UTF)\fR or \fI(*UCP)\fR special sequences. Inside a character class, \fI\\R\fR is treated as an unrecognized escape sequence, and causes an error.

.PP
\fIUnicode Character Properties\fR

.PP
When PCRE2 is built with Unicode support (the default), three additional escape sequences that match characters with specific properties are available. They can be used in any mode, though in 8-bit non-UTF modes these sequences are of course limited to testing characters whose code points are less than U+0100.

.PP
Matching characters by Unicode property is not fast, because PCRE2 has to do a multistage table lookup in order to find a character's property. That is why the traditional escape sequences such as \fI\\d\fR and \fI\\w\fR do not use Unicode properties in PCRE2 by default, though you can make them do so by setting the \fIucp\fR option or by starting the pattern with \fI(*UCP)\fR.

.PP
The extra escape sequences that provide property support are:

\p{_xx_}
.RS 2
a character with the _xx_ property


.RE
\P{_xx_}
.RS 2
a character without the _xx_ property


.RE
\X
.RS 2
a Unicode extended grapheme cluster


.RE

.PP
For compatibility with Perl, negation can be specified by including a circumflex between the opening brace and the property. For example, \fI\\p{^Lu}\fR is the same as \fI\\P{Lu}\fR.

.PP
In accordance with Unicode's "loose matching" rules, ASCII white space characters, hyphens, and underscores are ignored in the properties represented by _xx_ above. As well as the space character, ASCII white space can be tab, linefeed, vertical tab, formfeed, or carriage return.

.PP
Some properties are specified as a name only; others as a name and a value, separated by a colon or an equals sign. The names and values consist of ASCII letters and digits (with one Perl-specific exception, see below). They are not case sensitive. Note, however, that the escapes themselves, \fI\\p\fR and \fI\\P\fR, _are_ case sensitive. There are abbreviations for many names. The following examples are all equivalent:

.IP
.nf
\\p{bidiclass=al}
\\p{BC=al}
\\p{ Bidi_Class : AL }
\\p{ Bi-di class = Al }
\\P{ ^ Bi-di class = Al }

.fi

.PP
There is support for Unicode script names, Unicode general category properties, "Any", which matches any character (including newline), Bidi_Class, a number of binary (yes/no) properties, and some special PCRE2 properties (described below). Certain other Perl properties such as "InMusicalSymbols" are not supported by PCRE2. Note that \fI\\P{Any}\fR does not match any characters, so always causes a match failure.

.PP
\fIScript Properties for \fI\\p\fR and \fI\\P\fR\fR

.PP
There are three different syntax forms for matching a script. Each Unicode character has a basic script and, optionally, a list of other scripts ("Script Extensions") with which it is commonly used. Using the Adlam script as an example, \fI\\p{sc:Adlam}\fR matches characters whose basic script is Adlam, whereas \fI\\p{scx:Adlam}\fR matches, in addition, characters that have Adlam in their extensions list. The full names "script" and "script extensions" for the property types are recognized and, as for all property specifications, an equals sign is an alternative to the colon. If a script name is given without a property type, for example, \fI\\p{Adlam}\fR, it is treated as \fI\\p{scx:Adlam}\fR. Perl changed to this interpretation at release 5.26 and PCRE2 changed at release 10.40.

.PP
Unassigned characters are assigned the "Unknown" script. Others that are not part of an identified script are lumped together as "Common".

.PP
\fIThe General Category Property for \fI\\p\fR and \fI\\P\fR\fR

.PP
Each character has exactly one Unicode general category property, specified by a two-letter abbreviation. If only one letter is specified with \fI\\p\fR or \fI\\P\fR, it includes all the general category properties that start with that letter. In this case, in the absence of negation, the curly brackets in the escape sequence are optional; these two examples have the same effect:

.IP
.nf
\\p{L}
\\pL

.fi

.PP
The following general category property codes are supported:

C
.RS 2
Other


.RE
Cc
.RS 2
Control


.RE
Cf
.RS 2
Format


.RE
Cn
.RS 2
Unassigned


.RE
Co
.RS 2
Private use


.RE
Cs
.RS 2
Surrogate


.RE
L
.RS 2
Letter


.RE
Lc
.RS 2
Cased letter


.RE
Ll
.RS 2
Lower case letter


.RE
Lm
.RS 2
Modifier letter


.RE
Lo
.RS 2
Other letter


.RE
Lt
.RS 2
Title case letter


.RE
Lu
.RS 2
Upper case letter


.RE
M
.RS 2
Mark


.RE
Mc
.RS 2
Spacing mark


.RE
Me
.RS 2
Enclosing mark


.RE
Mn
.RS 2
Non-spacing mark


.RE
N
.RS 2
Number


.RE
Nd
.RS 2
Decimal number


.RE
Nl
.RS 2
Letter number


.RE
No
.RS 2
Other number


.RE
P
.RS 2
Punctuation


.RE
Pc
.RS 2
Connector punctuation


.RE
Pd
.RS 2
Dash punctuation


.RE
Pe
.RS 2
Close punctuation


.RE
Pf
.RS 2
Final punctuation


.RE
Pi
.RS 2
Initial punctuation


.RE
Po
.RS 2
Other punctuation


.RE
Ps
